<div type="definition">
<p>USE as GARMENT.</p>
    </div>
<div type="notes">
<div type="old-chinese-criteria">
<p>1. The current general word for wearing clothes or putting on clothes of any kind is yì 衣 (ant. tuō 脫 "take off").</p>
<p>2. Fú 服 (ant. xiè 卸 "take off") refers to dressing up for an official occasion.</p>
<p>3. Bèi 被 refers to putting on or wearing outer clothing of any kind, especially cloak-like garments.</p>
<p>4. Zhōng 衷 and zhōng 中 refer to wearing as underwear.</p>
<p>5. Biǎo 表 refers to wearing as outer visible clothes.</p>
<p>6. Dài 戴 refers to wearing something on one's head.</p>
<p>7. Lu# 履 refers to wearing something on one's feet.</p>
        </div>
<div type="modern-chinese-criteria">
<p>穿 is to wear whatever one inserts one's arms or legs into.</p>
<p>戴 is to wear on one's head.</p>
